snippet.textDisplay:
Did you know that President Nixon, and probably LBJ and JFK before him, had various pre-written announcements to be read if an Apollo mission went wrong? You can look up Nixon's speech for a scenario in which the Apollo 11 crew were still alive, but stranded on the Moon with no hope of returning to Earth. It's pretty chilling.

Anyway, I imagine that if you die in space, the bacteria on your skin and inside your body will cause at least partial decomposition. If the body is exposed to vacuum, though, that bacteria is not going to survive the vacuum either, save for the occasional extremophile. Without bacteria to cause it, organic decomposition cannot occur the way it does on Earth. I imagine that the end result would be something akin to a mummified bog body, but freeze-dried and very radioactive (from exposure to unfiltered solar radiation).
snippet.textOriginal:
Did you know that President Nixon, and probably LBJ and JFK before him, had various pre-written announcements to be read if an Apollo mission went wrong? Anyway, I imagine that if you die in space, the bacteria on your skin and inside your body will cause at least _partial_ decomposition. If the body is exposed to vacuum, though, that bacteria is not going to survive the vacuum either, save for the occasional extremophile.
